<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="UTF-8">
<title>Recovery Investigation Summary — {{ victim.name }}</title>
{% include "_styles.html.j2" %}
</head>
<body{% if draft %} class="draft" data-draft-label="{{ draft_label | default('DRAFT') }}"{% endif %}>

<section class="cover">
  <div class="cover-letterhead">
    <div class="cover-wordmark">
      Recupero
      <span class="tagline">Investigation Services</span>
    </div>
    <div class="cover-letterhead-right">
      <div class="confidential">Confidential — Client Summary</div>
      <div class="date">{{ generated_at }} UTC</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="cover-title-block">
    <div class="cover-eyebrow">Recovery Investigation</div>
    <h1>Findings &amp;<br/>Honest Next Steps</h1>
    <p class="cover-subtitle">
      We've completed the forensic trace of your wallet. The results
      are documented here. Unfortunately, the path your stolen funds
      took means we cannot pursue recovery through our standard
      issuer-freeze process. This summary explains what we found,
      what it means, and what you can still do.
    </p>
    <div class="cover-rule"></div>
  </div>

  <dl class="cover-meta">
    <div class="cover-meta-item">
      <dt>Prepared For</dt>
      <dd>{{ victim.name }}<span class="secondary">{% if victim.email %}{{ victim.email }}{% endif %}</span></dd>
    </div>
    <div class="cover-meta-item">
      <dt>Prepared By</dt>
      <dd>{{ investigator.name }}<span class="secondary">{{ investigator.organization }}<br/>{{ investigator.email }}</span></dd>
    </div>
    <div class="cover-meta-item">
      <dt>Case Reference</dt>
      <dd>{{ case_id }}</dd>
    </div>
    <div class="cover-meta-item">
      <dt>Affected Wallet</dt>
      <dd class="mono">{{ victim.wallet_address }}</dd>
    </div>
  </dl>
</section>

<div class="summary-box urgent">
  <p style="margin:0 0 0.7em 0;">
    <strong>Bottom line.</strong>
    We traced your wallet across {{ summary.addresses_traced }}
    addresses on {{ chain_display }}. {% if unrecoverable_reason_short %}{{ unrecoverable_reason_short }}{% else %}The funds did not end up in custody under any issuer we can practically request a freeze from.{% endif %}
    We do not believe we can help you recover the funds through our
    standard process.
  </p>
  <p style="margin:0;">
    <strong>Per our service agreement, $99 of your $499 fee is being
    refunded.</strong> The trace report, fund-flow diagram, and the
    law-enforcement handoff package are yours to keep regardless,
    and we recommend you use them as outlined in Section 4.
  </p>
</div>

<h2>1. What we did</h2>
<p>
  Following your engagement, we performed a forensic trace of the
  wallet at <span class="mono">{{ victim.wallet_address }}</span>
  on {{ chain_display }}. The trace followed every outbound
  transfer up to {{ max_depth }} {{ "hop" if max_depth == 1 else "hops" }}
  deep — meaning we tracked where your funds went, then where those
  recipient wallets sent them, and so on. The trace identified
  {{ summary.transfers }} transactions involving
  {{ summary.addresses_traced }} unique addresses.
</p>
<p>
  The full forensic detail — every transaction hash, exact USD value,
  block timestamp, and chain-explorer link — is in the attached
  <span class="mono">trace_report.html</span>. The fund-flow diagram
  (<span class="mono">{{ flow_filename | default("flow.svg") }}</span>)
  visualizes where your money moved.
</p>

<h2>2. Where the money went</h2>
{% if unrecoverable_explanation %}
<p>{{ unrecoverable_explanation }}</p>
{% else %}
<p>
  After tracing the perpetrator's movements through
  {{ max_depth }} {{ "hop" if max_depth == 1 else "hops" }}, the
  funds did not arrive at any address held under a stablecoin
  issuer's protocol-level authority. Without that issuer-level
  control point, there is no party from whom we can request a
  precautionary freeze. The trace report's destinations table
  shows the exact path the funds took.
</p>
{% endif %}

<h2>3. Why this means we can't help recover</h2>
<p>
  Recupero's recovery model relies on stablecoin issuers
  (Circle for USDC, Tether for USDT, Sky for DAI, Paxos for PYUSD)
  having protocol-level authority to freeze redemption of their
  tokens at any wallet. When stolen funds end up held as one of
  these stablecoins in an identifiable address, we can credibly
  request a freeze.
</p>
<p>
  In your case, the funds did not end up in this configuration.
  Common reasons (one of which applies to your case — the
  trace_report.html shows which):
</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Funds were laundered through a privacy mixer</strong>
      (Tornado Cash, Wasabi, etc.). After a mixer, the funds are
      pooled with other users' deposits and re-emerge at addresses
      we cannot link back to the original theft. Recovery from this
      point requires sophisticated chain-analysis tooling that
      typically only law-enforcement agencies have.</li>
  <li><strong>Funds were cashed out at a centralized exchange that
      has already processed the withdrawal.</strong> If the perpetrator
      deposited to a CEX and converted to fiat or other assets, the
      issuer no longer holds the position. Recovery from this point
      requires legal process against the exchange.</li>
  <li><strong>Funds remain in self-custody wallets with no issuer
      control.</strong> Native ETH, BTC, or other non-issuer assets
      held in standard wallets have no party with technical freeze
      authority. Only the holder of the private key can move them.</li>
  <li><strong>Recoverable amount is below the threshold where pursuit
      is economically rational.</strong> If less than $500 worth of
      identifiable stablecoin remains, the recovery cost exceeds
      the potential return.</li>
</ul>

<h2>4. What we recommend you do</h2>

<h3 style="margin-top:1.5em;">File with law enforcement</h3>
<p>
  The trace report and LE handoff package we're sending you are
  professionally formatted for direct submission to law enforcement.
  Even when our path can't help directly, an LE filing creates a
  formal record that has multiple benefits:
</p>
<ul>
  <li>It establishes your status as the victim of a theft, which is
      essential for any insurance claim or tax loss deduction.</li>
  <li>It feeds into the FBI's larger pattern-tracking — your case
      may be one of dozens by the same perpetrator, and law
      enforcement may be developing a case that includes yours.</li>
  <li>If the perpetrator is later identified and prosecuted, your
      filing puts you in the queue for restitution.</li>
  <li>For cases involving exchange withdrawals, the LE handoff
      identifies the exchange and provides the evidence basis for
      a subpoena. Law enforcement can subpoena exchanges for
      identifying information; private parties cannot.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Specifically, file with:</h3>
<ul>
  <li><strong>IC3 (FBI Internet Crime Complaint Center)</strong> at
      <a href="https://www.ic3.gov">ic3.gov</a> — federal portal,
      free, takes ~30 minutes. This is the canonical "I was a
      victim of crypto theft" filing.</li>
  <li><strong>Your local FBI field office</strong> if the loss is
      over $50,000 or involves a clear individual perpetrator.
      The field office can escalate to the FBI's Virtual Assets
      Unit. Submit the LE handoff package directly.</li>
  <li><strong>Your state's Attorney General consumer protection
      unit</strong> for any loss. Many states have dedicated
      cyber-crime liaisons.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Other considerations</h3>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Tax loss deduction.</strong> For US victims, theft
      losses on cryptocurrency may be deductible. The trace
      report provides the documentation a tax preparer needs to
      support the claim. Consult a CPA.</li>
  <li><strong>Insurance / employer benefits.</strong> Some homeowner's
      or umbrella policies cover cyber-theft losses. Some
      employers offer identity-theft programs that extend to
      crypto losses. The trace report serves as proof of incident.</li>
  <li><strong>Attorney consultation for large losses.</strong> If
      your loss exceeds $50,000, a 30-minute consultation with
      a crypto-recovery attorney (typically $200-$500) is worth
      it. Some firms work on contingency for high-value cases.</li>
</ul>

<h2>5. Your refund</h2>
<p>
  Per our service agreement, $99 of your $499 diagnostic fee is
  being refunded to the original payment method within 5 business
  days. The trace report, fund-flow diagram, and law-enforcement
  handoff package remain yours — they retain real value for the
  filings above even when our direct recovery path isn't available.
</p>

<h2>6. We're available for follow-up</h2>
<p>
  For 30 days from the date of this report, we're available at
  <a href="mailto:{{ investigator.email }}">{{ investigator.email }}</a>
  to answer clarification questions about the trace findings — for
  example, what to highlight when filing with IC3, or how to share
  the package with an attorney. No additional charge.
</p>
<p>
  If new information surfaces that changes the recovery picture
  (e.g., the exchange that received the funds is later subject to
  enforcement action and announces a victim-restitution process),
  we will reach out if your case appears eligible. We do this as
  a matter of professional care; no fee.
</p>

